      "content": "I'll add both clarifications to the `<replace>` documentation in the EDIT_FORMAT_XML section.\n\n<replace_zq7 file=\"forge/prompts/system.py\">\n<old_zq7>\n### Surgical Edits with `<replace>`\n\nTo change part of a file, find the exact text and replace it:\n\n```\n<replace file=\"path/to/file.py\">\n<old>\nexact text to find\n</old>\n<new>\nreplacement text\n</new>\n</replace>\n```\n\nRules:\n- The `<old>` text must match EXACTLY (whitespace, indentation, every character)\n- Only the first occurrence is replaced\n- You can include multiple `<replace>` blocks in one response\n- Edits are applied in order; if one fails, later edits are skipped\n- An empty `<new>` block deletes the matched text\n</old_zq7>\n<new_zq7>\n### Surgical Edits with `<replace>`\n\n`<replace>` is a **pure inline XML command** that you write directly in your\nresponse prose. It is **not** an API tool call \u2014 do not put it inside a\n`<function_calls>` block, do not invoke it via `update_context` or any other\nfunction. Just write the XML inline and the parser will pick it up.\n\nTo change part of a file, find the exact text and replace it:\n\n```\n<replace file=\"path/to/file.py\">\n<old>\nexact text to find\n</old>\n<new>\nreplacement text\n</new>\n</replace>\n```\n\nRules:\n- The `<old>` text must match EXACTLY (whitespace, indentation, every character)\n- Only the first occurrence is replaced\n- You can include multiple `<replace>` blocks in one response\n- Edits are applied in order; if one fails, later edits are skipped\n- An empty `<new>` block deletes the matched text\n\n### \u26a0\ufe0f Common Mistake: Wrong Closing Tag on `<new>`\n\nFor some reason there is a strong bias toward writing the closing tag of the\n`<new>` block as `</old>` instead of `</new>`, producing malformed structure\nlike:\n\n```\n<replace file=\"...\">\n<old>\n...\n</old>\n<new>\n...\n</old>      \u2190 WRONG! This must be </new>\n</replace>\n```\n\n**Before sending any `<replace>` block, glance at the four inner tags and\nconfirm the pattern is exactly:** `<old>` \u2026 `</old>` \u2026 `<new>` \u2026 `</new>`.\nMismatched closers will cause the edit to fail to parse.\n</new_zq7>\n</replace_zq7>\n\nDone. Added two clarifications to the `<replace>` docs in `forge/prompts/system.py`:\n\n1. An explicit note up front that `<replace>` is a pure inline XML command, not an API tool call \u2014 it shouldn't go inside `<function_calls>`.\n2. A \"Common Mistake\" callout warning about the bias toward closing `<new>` with `</old>`, with a visual of the wrong pattern and a reminder to verify the `<old>\u2026</old> <new>\u2026</new>` structure before sending.\n\nI used the nonced form (`_zq7`) for the edit because the body contains literal `</old>`, `</new>`, and `</replace>` tokens.",
